etal Grl on a Friday Night (2018) with Artist’s Statement -- tPart IV. BOUNDLESS KINSHIP -- tCHAPTER FOURTEEN. The Countdown Remix: Why Two Native Feminists Ride with Queen Bey -- tCHAPTER FIFTEEN. Slay Serigraph with Artist’s Statement -- tCHAPTER SIXTEEN. Mass Incarceration since 1492 -- tCHAPTER SEVENTEEN. “Liberation,”: Cover of Queer Indigenous Girl, Volume 4 & “Roots,” Cover of Black Indigenous Boy, Volume 2 -- tCHAPTER EIGHTEEN. Visual Cultures of Indigenous Futurism -- tCHAPTER NINETEEN. Diaspora, Transnationalism, and the Decolonial Project -- tCHAPTER TWENTY. Building Maroon Intellectual Communities -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe contributors to Otherwise Worlds investigate the complex relationships between settler colonialism and anti-Blackness to explore the political possibilities that emerge from such inquiries. Pointing out that presumptions of solidarity, antagonism, or incommensurability between Black and Native communities are insufficient to understand the relationships between the groups, the volume's scholars, artists, and activists look to articulate new modes of living and organizing in the service of creating new futures. Among other topics, they examine the ontological status of Blackness and Indigeneity, possible forms of relationality between Black and Native communities, perspectives on Black and Indigenous sociality, and freeing the flesh from the constraints of violence and settler colonialism. Throughout the volume's essays, art, and interviews, the contributors carefully attend to alternative kinds of relationships between Black and Native communities that can lead toward liberation. In so doing, they critically point to the importance of Black and Indigenous conversations for formulating otherwise worlds.ContributorsMaile Arvin, Marcus Briggs-Cloud, J. Kameron Carter, Ashon Crawley, Denise Ferreira da Silva, Chris Finley, Hotvlkuce Harjo, Sandra Harvey, Chad B. Infante, Tiffany Lethabo King, Jenell Navarro, Lindsay Nixon, Kimberly Robertson, Jared Sexton, Andrea Smith, Cedric Sunray, Se’mana Thompson, Frank B. Wilderson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aAfrican AmericansxRelations with Indians. 0aBlack peoplexStudy and teaching. 0aBlacksxStudy and teaching. 0aIndians of North AmericaxEthnic identity. 0aIndians of North AmericaxStudy and teaching. 0aRacexPolitical aspects. 0aRacism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh  asettler colonialism.1 aArvin, Maile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenito Infante, Chad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBriggs-Cloud, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, J. Kameron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawley, Ashon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerreira da Silva, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinley, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarjo, Hotvlkuce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Tiffany Lethabo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLethabo King, Tiffany, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNavarro, Jenell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNavarro, Jenell, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNixon, Lindsay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobertson, Kimb